Text Mining

The dataset contains 3,241 abstracts from articles collected via 5 PubMed searches. The search terms are listed in the second column, term and these will serve as the âdocuments.â Your job is to analyse these abstracts to find interesting insights.

  1. Tokenize the abstracts and count the number of each token. Do you see anything interesting? Does removing stop words change what tokens appear as the most frequent? What are the 5 most common tokens for each search term after removing stopwords?

Without grouping by search term, the top 10 search terms are stop words except for âcovidâ and â19â, revealing its importance in recent years of research, possibly across search term.

Without removing stopwords the most common words are stop words except for covid and 19 within each term. This may reveal that papers covid-19 were the most common among the 5 different PubMed searchers. After removing stopword, the trend continues with âcovidâ and â19â being the top 2 search terms. The rest of the top 10 search terms are related to search terms âprostateâ, âcancerâ, âpreâ, âeclampsiaâ, âpreeclampsiaâ and terms related to maternal health such as âwomenâ and âpregnancyâ.

After reviewing the top 5 words per search term (table above) , the tokens are all related directly to the serach term themselves. For example the top 2 terms related to cystic fibrosis are âcysticâ and âfibrosisâ

top_5_by_term <- abstracts %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%  
  group_by(term) %>%             
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 5) %>% #top 5 per search term not top 5 overall 
  ungroup()

  1. Calculate the TF-IDF value for each word-search term combination (here you want the search term to be the âdocumentâ). What are the 5 tokens from each search term with the highest TF-IDF value? How are the results different from the answers you got in question 1?

The TF-IDF scores in this output reveal the importance of each word within each search term. For example the words with the top TF-IDF values for the prostate cancer search term are âprostateâ, androgenâ, âpsaâ, âpostateectomyâ, and âcastrationâ, indicaitng the improance in using this temrinology in discussing prostate ccancer, but not as much in the topics related to the other search term.

This is more specific than identifying the top tokens per search term after removing stopwords in question 1. Question 1 only focuses on the raw counts and how often they appear after filtering. While these words relevant when discussing each term, they may not specifically reveal their importance, as TF-IDF scores give weights to terms that can appear often or not as much.

tf_idf <-  abstracts %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%                   
  count(term, word) %>%   
  group_by(term) %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) %>%                     
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>%                         
  top_n(5, tf_idf)  


kable(tf_idf, caption = "TF-IDF values for the Top 5 Words Per search Term")

Sentiment Analysis

  1. Perform a sentiment analysis using the NRC lexicon. What is the most common sentiment for each search term? What if you remove âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ from the list?

The most common sentiment for each term is positive, with only meningitis and prostate cancer having negative sentiments. From this one could guess that the papers regarding covid-19, cystic fibrosis, and preeclampsia are studies that lead to positive outcomes for patients with these conditions, however this sentiment analysis on positive/negative terms isnât intensive.

After removing âpositiveâ and ânegativeâ from the list, the sentiments are negative. For covid, meningitis, and prostate cancer its âfearâ, âdisgustâ with cystic fibrosis, and âanticipationâ with preeclampsia. Unlike the postive/negative analysis this may represent a lot of the feelings patients have upon diagnosis with tehse diseases and what these papers may do to address them.

abstracts %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>% 
  group_by(term) |> 
  summarise(sentiment = names(which.max(table(sentiment))))
# A tibble: 5 Ã 2

  1. Now perform a sentiment analysis using the AFINN lexicon to get an average positivity score for each abstract (hint: you may want to create a variable that indexes, or counts, the abstracts). Create a visualization that shows these scores grouped by search term. Are any search terms noticeably different from the others?

Most papers tend to have a negative positive score, however cystic fibrosis had an average positive score against the others (and with a much larger magnitude!). Without doing the PubMed search myself, my hope is that there is new advancements in cystic fibrosis mangment and treatment that are bieng shared, however a deeper sentimetn analysis is required.

options(repr.plot.width=12, repr.plot.height=8) # changing the size of this figure only

avg_by_abstract <- abstracts %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%                       
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn"), by = "word") %>%    
  group_by(term) %>%                                     
  summarise(sentiment = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE))


barplot(avg_by_abstract$sentiment,
        names.arg = avg_by_abstract$term,
        main = "Sentiment Analysis of the Average Positivity Score for Each Term",
        ylab = "Average Sentiment Score ( - = negative, + = positive"
